u30de\u30fc\u30af\u7d50\u679c\u3092\u8ff0\u3079\u307e\u3059\u3002","abstract_en":"CRuby adopts Mark Sweep GC Algorithm now.\nIn my presentation, I talk about Parallel Mark Algorithm that improves Mark.\nParallel mark divides a mark phase into a plurality of threads and it parallely execute.\nRecentlly, 8 core computers are not rare.\nIn such an enviroment, GC will be speed up, if it distribute tasks to each core.\nIn my presentation, I talk Parallel Mark Algorithm and Implemention, Resutl of benchmark.","code":"16S05","id":24,"kind":"session","position":1,"title":"CRubyGC\u306e\u4e26\u5217\u4e16\u754c","title_en":"Parallel world of CRuby's GC","speakers":[{"abstract":"GC\u597d\u304d\u306eRuby\u30b3\u30df\u30c3\u30bf\u3002\nRubyKaigi Driven Development(RDD)\u306b\u3088\u308bGC\u958b\u767a\u304c\u5f97\u610f\u3002\n\u6016\u3044\u8a00\u8449\u306f\u300cRevert\u3057\u3066\u304f\u3060\u3055\u3044\u300d","abstract_en":"I'm GC lover and Ruby commiter. \nI'm good at developing GC with RubyKaigi Driven Development(RDD).\nMy fearful words are \"Please revert\".","code":"16S05:1","id":12,"name":"nari","name_en":"nari","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:46Z","id":11,"name":"\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u30ef\u30fc\u30af\u5fdc\u7528\u901a\u4fe1\u7814\u7a76\u6240","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:46Z"}]}],"sessions":[]},{"abstract":"\u3061\u3087\u3063\u3068\u9055\u3063\u305f\u4e16\u754c\u306b\u306f\uff0c\u3053\u3093\u306a Ruby \u51e6\u7406\u7cfb\u304c\u3042\u3063\u305f\u304b\u3082\u3057\u308c\u307e\u305b\u3093\uff0e\u672c\u767a\u8868\u3067\u306f\uff0c\u305d\u3093\u306a\u3061\u3087\u3063\u3068\u9055\u3063\u305f Ruby \u51e6\u7406\u7cfb\u306e\u53ef\u80fd\u6027\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066\u7d39\u4ecb\u3057\u307e\u3059\uff0e\u305d\u3057\u3066\uff0c\u81ea\u5206\u3068\u3057\u3066\u306f\u3053\u3093\u306a\u4e16\u754c\u304c\u3044\u3044\u306a\uff0c Ruby \u51e6\u7406\u7cfb\u304c\u3042\u308b\u3068\u3044\u3044\u306a\uff0c\u3068\u3044\u3046\u3088\u3046\u306a\u8a71\u3092\u3057\u305f\u3044\u3068\u601d\u3044\u307e\u3059\uff0e","abstract_en":"If you live in a parallel world, it is possible that there is another\nversion of Ruby interpreter.  In this presentation, I will show the such\n\"different Ruby interpreters\".  Moreover, I will introduce the suitable\nworld, and Ruby interpreter for me.","code":"16S06","id":25,"kind":"session","position":1,"title":"\u4e26\u5217\u4e16\u754c\u306eRuby\u51e6\u7406\u7cfb","title_en":"Ruby Interpreters in the Parallel Worlds","speakers":[{"abstract":"CRuby\u30b3\u30df\u30c3\u30bf\uff08VM\u95a2\u9023\uff09\uff0e","abstract_en":"CRuby Commiter (VM).","code":"16S06:1","id":13,"name":"\u3055\u3055\u3060\u3053\u3046\u3044\u3061","name_en":"Koichi Sasada","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:46Z","id":12,"name":"\u6771\u4eac\u5927\u5b66\u5927\u5b66\u9662\u60c5\u5831\u7406\u5de5\u5b66\u7cfb\u7814\u7a76\u79d1","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:46Z"}]}],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:46Z","end_at":"2011-07-16T11:00:00Z","id":20,"place_area_id":1,"start_at":"2011-07-16T09:20:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:46Z","sessions":[{"abstract":null,"abstract_en":null,"code":"2011-07-16:S:dinner:1","id":28,"kind":"dinner","position":1,"title":"\u4f11\u61a9","title_en":"Break","speakers":[],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:48Z","end_at":"2011-07-17T00:50:00Z","id":24,"place_area_id":1,"start_at":"2011-07-17T00:30:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:48Z","sessions":[{"abstract":null,"abstract_en":null,"code":"2011-07-17:S:open:1","id":67,"kind":"open","position":35,"title":"\u958b\u5834","title_en":"Open","speakers":[],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:48Z","end_at":"2011-07-17T01:50:00Z","id":25,"place_area_id":1,"start_at":"2011-07-17T00:50:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:48Z","sessions":[{"abstract":"In view of the recent hardware developments , programmers should start focusing on enabling their programs for parallel execution.  The actor model is one promising model to handle concurrency and parallellism easily.\nThis talk discusses several options to use actors in Ruby.","abstract_en":"In view of the recent hardware developments , programmers should start focusing on enabling their programs for parallel execution.  The actor model is one promising model to handle concurrency and parallellism easily.\nThis talk discusses several options to use actors in Ruby.","code":"17S01","id":68,"kind":"session","position":35,"title":"Actors on stage","title_en":"Actors on stage","speakers":[{"abstract":"In the last 11 years, Elise\u2019s been rolling through jobs in C, C++, Java, a master in AI, before falling in love with Ruby and going freelance. Her experience in software development have helped her get a firm understanding on what works, what doesn\u2019t, and what will make you cry tears on nights before deadlines.\n\nShe\u2019s a jack of all trades, loves reading, tinkering, food, travel, learning, and people out of the ordinary.","abstract_en":"In the last 11 years, Elise\u2019s been rolling through jobs in C, C++, Java, a master in AI, before falling in love with Ruby and going freelance. Her experience in software development have helped her get a firm understanding on what works, what doesn\u2019t, and what will make you cry tears on nights before deadlines.\n\nShe\u2019s a jack of all trades, loves reading, tinkering, food, travel, learning, and people out of the ordinary.","code":"17S01:1","id":19,"name":"Elise Huard","name_en":"Elise Huard","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:48Z","id":18,"name":"Forward","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:48Z"}]}],"sessions":[]},{"abstract":"Rinda::TupleSpace\u306e\u6c38\u7d9a\u5316\u6a5f\u80fd\u306e\u767a\u8868\u304b\u3089\u6570\u5e74\u305f\u3061\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002\n\u672c\u8b1b\u6f14\u3067\u306f\u6c38\u7d9a\u7248Rinda\u306e\u53cd\u7701\u3068\u3001\u305d\u306e\u4e2d\u304b\u3089\u751f\u307e\u308c\u305f\n\u30b9\u30c8\u30ea\u30fc\u30e0\u6307\u5411\u540c\u671f\u6a5f\u69cb Drip \u3092\u7d39\u4ecb\u3057\u307e\u3059\u3002","abstract_en":"It's been several years since I last published `Rinda::TupleSpace`, the persistence layer on top of Rinda, the multi-process coordination library.  In this talk I will reexamine the pros and cons of Rinda and introduce the next generation streaming-orientated multi-process synchronisation library called \"Drip\".","code":"17S02","id":71,"kind":"session","position":35,"title":"Drip: Persistent tuple space and stream.","title_en":"Drip: Persistent tuple space and stream.","speakers":[{"abstract":"\u30d7\u30ed\u30b0\u30e9\u30de\u3002ERB, dRuby, Rinda\u306e\u4f5c\u8005\u3002\u30dd\u30b1\u30e2\u30f3WCS2010\u6803\u6728\u770c\u4ee3\u8868(\u30ab\u30fc\u30c9\u90e8\u9580)\u3002","abstract_en":"Programmer. Author of ERB, dRuby and Rinda.","code":"17M10_11:1","id":22,"name":"\u95a2\u5c06\u4fca","name_en":"Masatoshi SEKI","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:49Z","id":21,"name":"druby.org","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:49Z"}]}],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:49Z","end_at":"2011-07-17T02:00:00Z","id":27,"place_area_id":1,"start_at":"2011-07-17T01:50:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:49Z","sessions":[{"abstract":null,"abstract_en":null,"code":"2011-07-17:S:break:1","id":72,"kind":"break","position":35,"title":"\u4f11\u61a9","title_en":"Break","speakers":[],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:49Z","end_at":"2011-07-17T03:00:00Z","id":30,"place_area_id":1,"start_at":"2011-07-17T02:00:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:49Z","sessions":[{"abstract":"Writing Friendly Libraries will cover how to write libraries that are easy to use, extend and maintain.  My talk will cover techniques such as using plugin systems for extensibility and adding optional features.  I will also cover testing strategies and other tools to ease maintenance of software.","abstract_en":"Writing Friendly Libraries will cover how to write libraries that are easy to use, extend and maintain.  My talk will cover techniques such as using plugin systems for extensibility and adding optional features.  I will also cover testing strategies and other tools to ease maintenance of software.","code":"17S03","id":75,"kind":"session","position":35,"title":"Writing Friendly Libraries","title_en":"Writing Friendly Libraries","speakers":[{"abstract":"Eric Hodel has been a Rubyist for nearly a decade.  He became a committer to\nruby by writing documentation.  Eric now maintains RDoc and RubyGems and is a\nfounder of the Seattle Ruby Brigade.","abstract_en":"Eric Hodel has been a Rubyist for nearly a decade.  He became a committer to\nruby by writing documentation.  Eric now maintains RDoc and RubyGems and is a\nfounder of the Seattle Ruby Brigade.","code":"17S03:1","id":23,"name":"Eric Hodel","name_en":"Eric Hodel","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:49Z","id":22,"name":"Seattle Ruby Brigade, AT&T Interactive","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:49Z"}]}],"sessions":[]},{"abstract":"Using rails_best_practices gem can help you find bad smells in your rails codes, and tells you how to improve the codes quality. I will give you an in-depth exploration of rails_best_practices","abstract_en":"Using rails_best_practices gem can help you find bad smells in your rails codes, and tells you how to improve the codes quality. I will give you an in-depth exploration of rails_best_practices","code":"17S04","id":77,"kind":"session","position":35,"title":"Use rails_best_practices to refactor your rails codes","title_en":"Use rails_best_practices to refactor your rails codes","speakers":[{"abstract":"Richard Huang (a.k.a flyerhzm) is the senior rails engineer at OpenFeint. He currently lives in Beijing, he is the maintainer of rails_best_practices project, you can find more interesting projects on his github: https://github.com/flyerhzm","abstract_en":"Richard Huang (a.k.a flyerhzm) is the senior rails engineer at OpenFeint. He currently lives in Beijing, he is the maintainer of rails_best_practices project, you can find more interesting projects on his github: https://github.com/flyerhzm","code":"17S04:1","id":25,"name":"Richard Huang","name_en":"Richard Huang","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:50Z","id":24,"name":"OpenFeint","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:50Z"}]}],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:50Z","end_at":"2011-07-17T04:30:00Z","id":32,"place_area_id":1,"start_at":"2011-07-17T03:00:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:50Z","sessions":[{"abstract":null,"abstract_en":null,"code":"2011-07-17:S:lunch:1","id":79,"kind":"lunch","position":35,"title":"Lunch","title_en":"Lunch","speakers":[],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:50Z","end_at":"2011-07-17T05:30:00Z","id":34,"place_area_id":1,"start_at":"2011-07-17T04:30:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:50Z","sessions":[{"abstract":"Ruby\u306e\u7d44\u307f\u8fbc\u307f\u30af\u30e9\u30b9\u306e\u4e00\u3064\u3067\u3042\u308bThreadGroup\u306f\uff0cthread\u96c6\u5408\u3092\u6271\u3046\u969b\u306b\u6709\u7528\u306a\u3082\u306e\u3067\u3042\u308b\uff0ethread\u3092\u5358\u7d14\u306b\u96c6\u3081\u305f\u3082\u306e\u3092\u4e0a\u56de\u308b\u6d3b\u7528\u304c\u53ef\u80fd\u3067\u3042\u308b\u306f\u305a\u3060\u304c\uff0c\u5f93\u6765\u306f\u64cd\u4f5c\u30e1\u30bd\u30c3\u30c9\u304c\u5341\u5206\u306b\u5145\u5b9f\u3057\u3066\u3044\u308b\u3068\u306f\u8a00\u3048\u306a\u304b\u3063\u305f\uff0e\u672c\u767a\u8868\u3067\u306f\uff0cThreadGroup\u5f37\u5316\u306e\u5185\u5bb9\u3068\u610f\u56f3\u3068\u3092\uff0c\u7528\u4f8b\u3092\u4ea4\u3048\u306a\u304c\u3089\u7d39\u4ecb\u3059\u308b\uff0e","abstract_en":"ThreadGroup class, which is one of the embedded classes of Ruby, is useful for managing sets of threads. Although a ThreadGroup object should have advantages over a simple list of threads, it hasn't had enough methods to do that. In this presentation, I'll introduce details and intentions of improving ThreadGroup with some usages.","code":"17S05","id":81,"kind":"session","position":35,"title":"ThreadGroup\u30af\u30e9\u30b9\u306e\u5f37\u5316\u3068\u305d\u306e\u5229\u7528\u6cd5","title_en":"Improvement of ThreadGroup class and its usage","speakers":[{"abstract":"\u6c38\u4e95\u79c0\u5229 (\u6c38\u4e95\uff20\u77e5\u80fd\uff0e\u4e5d\u5de5\u5927) \u306f Ruby/Tk \u306e\u958b\u767a\u8005\u3067\u3042\u308b\uff0eRuby \u306f\u5f7c\u306e\u672c\u696d\u306e\u7814\u7a76 (\u30bd\u30d5\u30c8\u30a6\u30a7\u30a2\u5de5\u5b66\u306e\u5206\u91ce\u3067\u306f\u306a\u3044) \u3067\u306e\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u51e6\u7406\u306e\u969b\u306e\u304a\u6c17\u306b\u5165\u308a\u306e\u9053\u5177\u3068\u306a\u3063\u3066\u3044\u308b\uff0e","abstract_en":"Hidetoshi NAGAI is a developer of Ruby/Tk. Ruby is a favorite tool for data processing on his research work (which doesn't belong to the domain of software engineering).","code":"17S05:1","id":27,"name":"\u6c38\u4e95 \u79c0\u5229","name_en":"Hidetoshi NAGAI","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:50Z","id":26,"name":"\u4e5d\u5dde\u5de5\u696d\u5927\u5b66 / Rubyist\u4e5d\u5dde","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:50Z"}]}],"sessions":[]},{"abstract":"JIS X 3017\u306f\u30d7\u30ed\u30b0\u30e9\u30df\u30f3\u30b0\u8a00\u8a9eRuby\u306e\u65e5\u672c\u56fd\u5185\u898f\u683c\u3067\u3042\u308b\u3002\u3053\u306e\u8b1b\u6f14\u3067\u306f\uff0c\u3053\u306e\u898f\u683c\u53ca\u3073Ruby\u81ea\u8eab\u304c\u306a\u305c\u304b\u304f\u3082\u8907\u96d1\u3067\u3042\u308b\u304b\u3092\u8aac\u660e\u3059\u308b\u3002","abstract_en":"JIS X 3017 is the Japanese national standard of the Ruby programming language.  This talk explains why the standard and Ruby itself are so complex.","code":"17S06","id":82,"kind":"session","position":35,"title":"JIS X 3017\u306e\u8aad\u307f\u65b9","title_en":"How to read JIS X 3017","speakers":[{"abstract":"Ruby\u30b3\u30df\u30c3\u30bf","abstract_en":"a Ruby committer","code":"17S06:1","id":28,"name":"\u524d\u7530 \u4fee\u543e","name_en":"Shugo Maeda","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:50Z","id":27,"name":"\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u30ef\u30fc\u30af\u5fdc\u7528\u901a\u4fe1\u7814\u7a76\u6240","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:50Z"}]}],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:51Z","end_at":"2011-07-17T05:40:00Z","id":35,"place_area_id":1,"start_at":"2011-07-17T05:30:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:51Z","sessions":[{"abstract":null,"abstract_en":null,"code":"2011-07-17:S:break:2","id":84,"kind":"break","position":35,"title":"\u4f11\u61a9","title_en":"Break","speakers":[],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:51Z","end_at":"2011-07-17T06:40:00Z","id":38,"place_area_id":1,"start_at":"2011-07-17T05:40:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:51Z","sessions":[{"abstract":"JRuby\u306e\u4e3b\u306a\u30e1\u30ea\u30c3\u30c8\u306f\u3001Java\u30af\u30e9\u30b9\u3092\u30a4\u30f3\u30dd\u30fc\u30c8\u3057\u3066\u3001\u305d\u308c\u3092PORO(Plain Old Ruby Object)\u306e\u3088\u3046\u306b\u4f7f\u3048\u308b\u3053\u3068\u3067\u3059\u3002\n\u3053\u308c\u3067\u3001Java\u304c\u3072\u3068\u3068\u304d\u306e\u3088\u3046\u306b\u307e\u305f\u307e\u305f\u697d\u3057\u304f\u306a\u308a\u307e\u3059\u3002\nJava\u306e\u30ec\u30ac\u30b7\u30fc\u30b3\u30fc\u30c9\u3092\u4f7f\u3063\u3066\u3001Ruby\u30b3\u30fc\u30c9\u306b\u7d20\u6575\u306a\u611f\u3058\u3067\u5165\u308c\u3089\u308c\u308bAPI\u3092\u4f5c\u308a\u3042\u3052\u308b\u3053\u3068\u304c\u3067\u304d\u307e\u3059\u3002\u65e2\u5b58\u306eRuby\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6\u30e9\u30ea\u306b\u4e0d\u8db3\u3057\u3066\u3044\u308b\u6a5f\u80fd\u3092\u57cb\u3081\u308b\u305f\u3081\u306b\u65b0\u3057\u3044Java\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6\u30e9\u30ea\u3084\u5b9f\u7e3e\u306e\u3042\u308b\u5805\u56fa\u306aJava\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6\u30e9\u30ea\u306b\u30a2\u30af\u30bb\u30b9\u3059\u308b\u3053\u3068\u304c\u3067\u304d\u308b\u306e\u3067\u3059\u3002\n\n\u3053\u306e\u30bb\u30c3\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u3067\u306f\u6b21\u306e\u3088\u3046\u306a\u3053\u3068\u3092\u8a71\u3057\u307e\u3059:\n\n  * Ruby\u30b3\u30fc\u30c9\u306e\u4e2d\u304b\u3089Java\u30af\u30e9\u30b9\u3092\u4f7f\u3046\u305f\u3081\u306e\u57fa\u672c\n  * Ruby\u306e\u30d6\u30ed\u30c3\u30af\u3084\u30af\u30e9\u30b9\u3092\u3064\u304b\u3063\u3066Java\u306e\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u30d5\u30a7\u30fc\u30b9\u3092\u5b9f\u88c5\u3059\u308b\u65b9\u6cd5\n  * \u6ce8\u610f\u3059\u3079\u304d\u70b9\n  * Ruby\u306b\u30de\u30c3\u30c1\u3059\u308bJava API\u3092\u8a2d\u8a08\u3059\u308b\u30d2\u30f3\u30c8\n\u3053\u306e\u30bb\u30c3\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u3092\u805e\u3044\u305f\u4eba\u304c\u3001Ruby\u304b\u3089Java\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6\u30e9\u30ea\u3092\u4e0a\u624b\u306b\u4fbf\u5229\u306b\u6d3b\u7528\u3067\u304d\u308b\u3088\u3046\u306b\u306a\u308b\u3053\u3068\u3092\u610f\u56f3\u3057\u3066\u3044\u307e\u3059\u3002","abstract_en":"One major benefit of JRuby is the ability to import Java classes and then use them as if they were POROs (Plain Old Ruby Objects). This feature makes Java fun again. You can pull in legacy code and sculpt an API which fits nicely into your Ruby code. You can access novel or robust Java libraries to bridge a gap in existing Ruby libraries.\n\nThis talk will:\n\n    * Show basics of interacting with Java classes from within Ruby\n    * Implementing Java interfaces with Ruby blocks and classes\n    * Point out Gotchas\n    * Give style hints to make Java APIs fit better into the Ruby way\n\nBy the end of this talk you should be able to effectively consume Java libraries in Ruby in a way that is satisfying and useful.","code":"17S07","id":87,"kind":"session","position":35,"title":"Java in Ruby: Scripting Java in JRuby","title_en":"Java in Ruby: Scripting Java in JRuby","speakers":[{"abstract":"\u30c8\u30fc\u30de\u30b9\u30fb\u30a8\u30cd\u30dc\u30fc\u306f\u300110\u5e74\u4ee5\u4e0aJava\u3092\u3084\u3063\u3066\u3044\u308b\u719f\u7df4Java\u30a8\u30f3\u30b8\u30cb\u30a2\u3067\u3001JRuby\u30d7\u30ed\u30b8\u30a7\u30af\u30c8\u306e\u30ea\u30fc\u30c0\u30fc\u306e\u4e00\u4eba\u3067\u3059\u3002\u307e\u305f\u30012001\u304b\u3089\u697d\u3057\u304fRuby\u3092\u4f7f\u3063\u3066\u3044\u307e\u3059\u3002JRuby\u306e\u4ed5\u4e8b\u306b\u52a0\u3048\u3066\u3001JVM\u4e0a\u3067\u52d5\u304fJava\u4ee5\u5916\u306e\u8a00\u8a9e\u306e\u72b6\u6cc1\u3092\u9032\u5c55\u3055\u305b\u308b\u3053\u3068\u306b\u95a2\u5fc3\u304c\u3042\u308a\u307e\u3059\u3002\u73fe\u5728\u306fEngine Yard\u306b\u52e4\u3081\u3066\u304a\u308a\u3001\u30d5\u30eb\u30bf\u30a4\u30e0\u3067JRuby\u306e\u4ed5\u4e8b\u3092\u3057\u3066\u3044\u307e\u3059\u3002","abstract_en":"Thomas Enebo has been a practitioner of Java for over a decade and he is the co-lead of the JRuby project. Thomas has also been happily using Ruby since 2001. In addition to working on JRuby, Tom is interested in improving the state of alternative languages on the Java Virtual Machine. Tom is employed working on JRuby full time at Engine Yard.","code":"17S07:1","id":30,"name":"\u30c8\u30fc\u30de\u30b9\u30fbE\u30fb\u30a8\u30cd\u30dc","name_en":"Thomas E Enebo","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:51Z","id":29,"name":"jruby.org / Engine Yard","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:51Z"}]},{"abstract":"JRuby\u3092\u4f7f\u3063\u3066\u30af\u30e9\u30a6\u30c9\u30d7\u30e9\u30c3\u30c8\u30d5\u30a9\u30fc\u30e0\u3092\u958b\u767a\u3057\u3066\u3044\u308b\u3002\u65e5\u672cJRuby\u30e6\u30fc\u30b6\u30fc\u4f1a\u3067JRubyKaigi 2010\u5b9f\u884c\u59d4\u54e1\u9577\u3067JRubyKaigi 2011\u306e\u30b9\u30bf\u30c3\u30d5\u3002","abstract_en":"He is developing a cloud platform service with JRuby for his company. A member of JRuby user meetup. He was the organizer of JRubyKaigi 2010 and is a staff of JRubyKaigi 2011.","code":"17S07:2","id":31,"name":"\u5927\u5834\u5149\u4e00\u90ce","name_en":"Koichiro Ohba","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:51Z","id":30,"name":"\u65e5\u672cJRuby\u30e6\u30fc\u30b6\u30fc\u4f1a","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:51Z"}]}],"sessions":[]},{"abstract":"2011\u5e743\u6708\u6642\u70b9\u3067\u306eMacRuby\u306fRuby\u51e6\u7406\u7cfb\u3068\u3057\u3066\u306e\u5b8c\u6210\u5ea6\u306f\u4f4e\u304f\u3001Ruby on\nRails\u304c\u5230\u5e95\u52d5\u4f5c\u3059\u308b\u3088\u3046\u306b\u306f\u601d\u3048\u306a\u3044\u3002\u3057\u304b\u3057\u306a\u304c\u3089\u3001MacRuby\u306b\u5bfe\u3057\u3066\u6539\u826f\n\u306b\u6539\u826f\u3092\u91cd\u306d\u308b\u3053\u3068\u3067\u304d\u3063\u3068Rails\u3092\u52d5\u4f5c\u3055\u305b\u308b\u3053\u3068\u304c\u3067\u304d\u308b\uff08\u306f\u305a\u3067\u3042\u308b\uff09\u3002\n\n\u672c\u767a\u8868\u3067\u306fMacRuby\u3067Rails\u3092\u52d5\u4f5c\u3055\u305b\u308b\u305f\u3081\u306b\u5fc5\u8981\u3060\u3063\u305f\u4fee\u6b63\u5185\u5bb9\u3068\u3068\u3082\u306b\u3001\n\u305d\u306e\u904e\u7a0b\u3067\u3042\u3089\u305f\u3081\u3066\u77e5\u308b\u3053\u3068\u306b\u306a\u3063\u305fcRuby\u306e\u3059\u3070\u3089\u3057\u3055\u3092\u8aac\u660e\u3057\u307e\u3059\u3002","abstract_en":"MacRuby is an implementation of Ruby 1.9 that is directly on top of Mac OS X core technologies. Recently, MacRuby has become viable as a tool for developing useful desktop applications for Mac OS X.\nHowever, as of March 2011, MacRuby is still missing some functionality that is present in cRuby. Therefore, MacRuby is not able to run Ruby on Rails.\nIn my presentation, I will explain how I modified MacRuby to make it a suitable foundation for running Rails. I would also like to explain some of technical intricacies that I discovered along the way.","code":"17S08","id":88,"kind":"session","position":35,"title":"MacRuby on Rails \u301cMacRuby\u304b\u3089\u898b\u305fcRuby\u301c","title_en":"MacRuby on Rails","speakers":[{"abstract":"MRI\u30e1\u30f3\u30c6\u30ca\u306e\u4e00\u4eba\u3002\u62c5\u5f53\u306fReadline\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6\u30e9\u30ea\u3067\u3059\u3002","abstract_en":"Kouji Takao is one of the commiter of MRI.\nHe is maintener of Readline of Ruby.","code":"17S08:1","id":32,"name":"\u9ad8\u5c3e\u5b8f\u6cbb","name_en