7Perl\u306b\u89e6\u308c\u305a\u306b\u3069\u3053\u307e\u3067\u884c\u3051\u308b\u304b\u30c1\u30ad\u30f3\u30ec\u30fc\u30b9\u771f\u3063\u6700\u4e2d\u3002","abstract_en":"ANDO Yasushi is a perl hater working for a campany mainly using perl.","code":"18S01:1","id":39,"name":"\u3042\u3093\u3069\u3046\u3084\u3059\u3057","name_en":"ANDO Yasushi","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:54Z","id":36,"name":"\u30df\u30af\u30b7\u30a3\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:54Z"}]}],"sessions":[]},{"abstract":"\u30b0\u30ea\u30c3\u30c1\u3001\u7279\u306b\u753b\u50cf\u3084\u6620\u50cf\u306b\u304a\u3051\u308b\u30f4\u30a3\u30b8\u30e5\u30a2\u30eb\u30fb\u30b0\u30ea\u30c3\u30c1\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066\u7d39\u4ecb\u3057\u307e\u3059\u3002\n\u30b0\u30ea\u30c3\u30c1\u3092\u751f\u6210\u3059\u308b\u3044\u304f\u3064\u304b\u306eRuby\u30b9\u30af\u30ea\u30d7\u30c8\u3068\u3001\u52d5\u753b\u3092\u30b0\u30ea\u30c3\u30c1\u3059\u308bRuby\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6\u30e9\u30ea AviGlitch \u3092\u7528\u3044\u3064\u3064\u3001\n\u30b0\u30ea\u30c3\u30c1\u3068\u306f\u4f55\u304b\u3001\u3069\u306e\u3088\u3046\u306b\u3057\u3066\u3064\u304f\u3089\u308c\u308b\u306e\u304b\u3001\u3092\u5b9f\u4f8b\u3092\u793a\u3057\u306a\u304c\u3089\u89e3\u8aac\u3057\u307e\u3059\u3002","abstract_en":"The \"visual glitch\" is an artifact view of corrupted image/video data.\nSome art people say that \"true\" glitch can't be reproduced, but I\nthink they are just unfamiliar with how computers work.\nWe, programmers, can learn about file format specs, binary\ncompositions, and can make reproducible glitches with programming.\nThis talk, with examples, some Ruby snippets and my library AviGlitch,\nwill show you how to generate glitched images/videos.","code":"18S02","id":118,"kind":"session","position":46,"title":"Visual Glitch, using Ruby","title_en":"Visual Glitch, using Ruby","speakers":[{"abstract":"\u30a6\u30a7\u30d6\u30d7\u30ed\u30b0\u30e9\u30de\u30fc\u3001\u30b0\u30ea\u30c3\u30c1\u6620\u50cf\u306a\u3069\u3082\u4f5c\u308a\u307e\u3059\u3002","abstract_en":"ucnv is a web developer and visual artist based in Tokyo. In 2009, he\ndeveloped a Ruby library to make broken videos, named AviGlitch. He\nspends a lot of time destroying images or videos. He uses these broken\nthings for visual live performances, VJs and music videos.","code":"18S02:1","id":42,"name":"ucnv","name_en":"ucnv","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:54Z","id":39,"name":"Independent","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:54Z"}]}],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:54Z","end_at":"2011-07-18T02:00:00Z","id":56,"place_area_id":1,"start_at":"2011-07-18T01:50:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:54Z","sessions":[{"abstract":null,"abstract_en":null,"code":"2011-07-18:S:break:1","id":120,"kind":"break","position":46,"title":"\u4f11\u61a9","title_en":"Break","speakers":[],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:55Z","end_at":"2011-07-18T03:00:00Z","id":58,"place_area_id":1,"start_at":"2011-07-18T02:00:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:55Z","sessions":[{"abstract":"Fear, uncertainty and doubt stopping you from playing with shiny new rubies? Not sure that they're exactly the same as the one you're currently using? Let the Small Eigen Collider smash them up and see what they're made of!\n\nThe Small Eigen Collider uses reflection and metaprogramming to create random Ruby code. The code can be run under different implementations, and the results compared to detect inconsistencies between the versions.\n\nSo accelerate your Rubies towards the speed of light and see what gets produced. And don't worry about the black holes - the program has created many of them already in the form of  segmentation faults!","abstract_en":"Fear, uncertainty and doubt stopping you from playing with shiny new rubies? Not sure that they're exactly the same as the one you're currently using? Let the Small Eigen Collider smash them up and see what they're made of!\n\nThe Small Eigen Collider uses reflection and metaprogramming to create random Ruby code. The code can be run under different implementations, and the results compared to detect inconsistencies between the versions.\n\nSo accelerate your Rubies towards the speed of light and see what gets produced. And don't worry about the black holes - the program has created many of them already in the form of  segmentation faults!","code":"18S03","id":122,"kind":"session","position":46,"title":"\u5c0f\u578b\u7279\u7570\u885d\u7a81\u578b\u52a0\u901f\u5668\u3067Ruby\u5185\u306e\u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30af\u30db\u30fc\u30eb\u306e\u7279\u7570\u70b9\u3092\u898b\u3064\u3051\u308b\u65b9\u6cd5","title_en":"Finding Black Holes in Ruby with the Small Eigen Collider","speakers":[{"abstract":"\u30d0\u30a4\u30aa\u30a4\u30f3\u30d5\u30a9\u30de\u30c6\u30a3\u30af\u30b9\u306e\u79d1\u5b66\u8005","abstract_en":"Andrew Grimm is a bioinformatician at the University of New South Wales in Sydney, Australia. He came across Ruby while using Rails at his previous job associated with the Encyclopedia of Life, but now specialises in Plain Old Ruby Objects. Previous projects (outside of work) analyzed why you always end up at \"Philosophy\" in Wikipedia, and a mutation tester in which zombies eat your brains unless your unit tests can kill them all.","code":"18S03:1","id":45,"name":"\u30a2\u30f3\u30c9\u30ea\u30e5\u30fc \u30b0\u30ea\u30e0","name_en":"Andrew Grimm","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:55Z","id":42,"name":"\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30b5\u30a6\u30b9\u30a6\u30a7\u30fc\u30eb\u30ba\u5927\u5b66 (UNSW)","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:55Z"}]}],"sessions":[]},{"abstract":"2011\u5e74\uff13\u670811\u65e5\u306b\u304a\u304d\u305f\u6771\u65e5\u672c\u5927\u9707\u707d\u3068\u6d25\u6ce2\u306b\u3088\u3063\u3066\u6771\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u5404\u5730\u306b\u304a\u3044\u3066\u904e\u53bb\u306b\u4f8b\u304c\u306a\u3044\u307b\u3069\u306e\u591a\u5927\u306a\u88ab\u5bb3\u3092\u3046\u3051\u307e\u3057\u305f\u304c\u3001\u305d\u308c\u3068\u540c\u6642\u306b\n\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u30cd\u30c3\u30c8\u3084\u30bd\u30fc\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30e1\u30c7\u30a3\u30a2\u3092\u901a\u3058\u3066\u69d8\u3005\u306a\u6d3b\u52d5\u304c\u30dc\u30e9\u30f3\u30c6\u30a3\u30a2\u306e\u624b\u306b\u3088\u3063\u3066\u304a\u3053\u306a\u308f\u308c\u3066\u304d\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3057\u3001\u73fe\u5728\u3082\u304a\u3053\u306a\u308f\u308c\u3066\u3044\u307e\u3059\u3002\n\u3053\u306e\u30c8\u30fc\u30af\u3067\u306f\u5730\u9707\u767a\u751f\u76f4\u5f8c\u306b\u3069\u306e\u3088\u3046\u306a\u6d3b\u52d5\u304c\u884c\u308f\u308c\u305f\u304b\u3001\u73fe\u5728\u3069\u306e\u3088\u3046\u306a\u6d3b\u52d5\u304c\u884c\u308f\u308c\u3066\u3044\u308b\u304b\u3001\u305d\u3057\u3066\u6211\u3005Rubyist\u304c\u3069\u306e\u3088\u3046\u306a\u5f62\u3067\n\u95a2\u308f\u3063\u3066\u3044\u304f\u4e8b\u304c\u3067\u304d\u308b\u304b\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066\u4e00\u7dd2\u306b\u8003\u3048\u3066\u3044\u304f\u5834\u3068\u3057\u305f\u3044\u3068\u601d\u3044\u307e\u3059\u3002\n\u6d77\u5916\u304b\u3089\u304a\u8d8a\u3057\u306eRubyist\u306e\u307f\u306a\u3055\u3093\u306b\u7279\u306b\u805e\u3044\u3066\u3044\u305f\u3060\u304d\u305f\u3044\u306e\u3067\u82f1\u8a9e\u3067\u306e\u8b1b\u6f14\u3092\u4e88\u5b9a\u3057\u3066\u3044\u307e\u3059\u3002","abstract_en":"The Great Eastern Japan Earthquake on March 11th caused devastating impact across Japan. However, there were numerous efforts amongst Japanese hackers to help the disaster hit areas. Throughout this talk, I will explain what kind of activities occurred right after the earthquake, and will discuss what we can do as Rubyists to help the people affected by the disaster. The talk will be done in English.","code":"18S04","id":123,"kind":"session","position":46,"title":"3/11 \u305d\u3057\u3066Rubyist\u3068\u3057\u3066\u3067\u304d\u308b\u3053\u3068","title_en":"The Great Eastern Japan Earthquake and what you can do as a Rubyist ?","speakers":[{"abstract":"\u4e95\u4e0a\u771f(New Bamboo)\n2004\u5e74\u304b\u3089\u30ed\u30f3\u30c9\u30f3\u306b\u5728\u4f4f\u4e2d\u306e\u9006\u8f38\u5165Rubyist\uff08\u65e5\u672c\u306b\u3044\u308b\u6642\u306fRuby\u306e\u3053\u3068\u77e5\u308a\u307e\u305b\u3093\u3067\u3057\u305f\u3002\u3059\u307f\u307e\u305b\u3093\uff09\u3002\u5143DBA(Sybase)\u30022010\u306eRubyKaigi\u3067\u306f\u300c\u30ea\u30a2\u30eb\u30bf\u30a4\u30e0\u30a6\u30a7\u30d6\u304c\u3067\u304d\u308b\u307e\u3067\u300d\u3068\u3044\u3046\u30c8\u30d4\u30c3\u30af\u3067\u767a\u8868\u3002http://sinsai.info","abstract_en":"Rubyist living in London since 2004 (though did not know about Ruby when I was in Japan. Sorry..)\nex-DBA(Sybase). Gave a talk \"Building real time web\" at RubyKaigi 2010 . Working under translation team of http://sinsai.info , earthquake information mapping site.  Currently translating dRuby book into English (due to be published under pragpub)","code":"18S04:1","id":46,"name":"\u4e95\u4e0a\u771f","name_en":"Makoto Inoue","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:55Z","id":43,"name":"New Bamboo","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:55Z"}]},{"abstract":"\u95a2\u6cbb\u4e4b\nGeorepublic Japan CEO. \u30aa\u30fc\u30d7\u30f3\u30bd\u30fc\u30b9\u30bd\u30d5\u30c8\u30a6\u30a7\u30a2\u3092\u4f7f\u3063\u305fGIS \u30b5\u30fc\u30d3\u30b9\u306e\u958b\u767a\u3002Geo\u958b\u767a\u8005\u3068\u3057\u3066\uff15\u5e74\u4ee5\u4e0a\u306e\u7d4c\u9a13\u3042\u308a\u3002\u904e\u53bb\uff13\u5e74\u306e\u9593\u3001\u6700\u5927\u898f\u6a21\u306eGeoWeb\u30b5\u30fc\u30d3\u30b9\u3092\u4e3b\u50ac","abstract_en":"CEO of Georepublic Japan, a company providing gis-development service using open source software. He have been working as a geo developer over five years. He has been organizing one of biggest free conference for Geoweb services in Japan over three years.","code":"18S04:2","id":47,"name":"\u95a2\u6cbb\u4e4b","name_en":"Hal Seki","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:55Z","id":44,"name":"\u30b7\u30ea\u30a6\u30b9\u30c6\u30af\u30ce\u30ed\u30b8\u30fc\u30ba, Geo Republic Japan, \u30aa\u30fc\u30d7\u30f3\u30b9\u30c8\u30ea\u30fc\u30c8\u30de\u30c3\u30d7\u30fb\u30d5\u30a1\u30a6\u30f3\u30c7\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u30fb\u30b8\u30e3\u30d1\u30f3, sinsai.info","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:55Z"}]}],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:56Z","end_at":"2011-07-18T04:30:00Z","id":61,"place_area_id":1,"start_at":"2011-07-18T03:00:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:56Z","sessions":[{"abstract":null,"abstract_en":null,"code":"2011-07-18:S:lunch:1","id":126,"kind":"lunch","position":46,"title":"Lunch","title_en":"Lunch","speakers":[],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:56Z","end_at":"2011-07-18T05:30:00Z","id":63,"place_area_id":1,"start_at":"2011-07-18T04:30:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:56Z","sessions":[{"abstract":"DataMapper is a storage engine agnostic ORM, it can work just as well with a RDMS as with any another type of storage engine such as, but not limited to: no sequel stores (redis, mongo...), XML or yaml data source, etc.  While many adapters already exist to connect DataMapper to a miriad of storage engines, there may not be one for your preferred storage engine or you may need to communicate with data from a legacy system.  If this is the case I will introduce you to the clean and simple API used to write your custom DataMapper adapter.","abstract_en":"DataMapper is a storage engine agnostic ORM, it can work just as well with a RDMS as with any another type of storage engine such as, but not limited to: no sequel stores (redis, mongo...), XML or yaml data source, etc.  While many adapters already exist to connect DataMapper to a miriad of storage engines, there may not be one for your preferred storage engine or you may need to communicate with data from a legacy system.  If this is the case I will introduce you to the clean and simple API used to write your custom DataMapper adapter.","code":"18S05","id":129,"kind":"session","position":46,"title":"Writing custom DataMapper Adapters","title_en":"Writing custom DataMapper Adapters","speakers":[{"abstract":"I am a ruby/rails developer working for OptimisCorp in Taiwan.  I haven been involved with ruby, personally and professionally, for over 2 years.  I tend to enjoy deploying to the cloud and have spent a lot of time working with Ruby on the Google App Engine.  You can find more about me at github: https://github.com/joshsmoore.","abstract_en":"I am a ruby/rails developer working for OptimisCorp in Taiwan.  I haven been involved with ruby, personally and professionally, for over 2 years.  I tend to enjoy deploying to the cloud and have spent a lot of time working with Ruby on the Google App Engine.  You can find more about me at github: https://github.com/joshsmoore.","code":"18S05:1","id":51,"name":"Joshua Moore","name_en":"Joshua Moore","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:56Z","id":47,"name":"Optimis International","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:56Z"}]}],"sessions":[]},{"abstract":"It was Ruby on Rails that called my attention back in 2005. There were not many people using Ruby in Brazil back then. There were no established community and no market to work with. So, I had a dilemma: I want to work full time with Ruby, but there was no market for me to work for. What to do? Move to the USA or give up and continue in the ever growing Java market. Or maybe, take a completely unexpected route: create my own local market. Impossible? Reckless?\nIn this talk I'd like to explain why I like Ruby and how it enabled us to grow a sustainable community and market in Brazil. As a short summary and spoiler for the talk: yes, there is now a very good and healthy local market for Ruby in Brazil, several small and big companies using Ruby, several consulting companies offering Ruby services, lots of great developers contributing back to the global community, big conferences such as our own RubyConf Brazil. So yes, it worked! And no, I didn't have to move out to the USA to work full time with Ruby!","abstract_en":"It was Ruby on Rails that called my attention back in 2005. There were not many people using Ruby in Brazil back then. There were no established community and no market to work with. So, I had a dilemma: I want to work full time with Ruby, but there was no market for me to work for. What to do? Move to the USA or give up and continue in the ever growing Java market. Or maybe, take a completely unexpected route: create my own local market. Impossible? Reckless?\nIn this talk I'd like to explain why I like Ruby and how it enabled us to grow a sustainable community and market in Brazil. As a short summary and spoiler for the talk: yes, there is now a very good and healthy local market for Ruby in Brazil, several small and big companies using Ruby, several consulting companies offering Ruby services, lots of great developers contributing back to the global community, big conferences such as our own RubyConf Brazil. So yes, it worked! And no, I didn't have to move out to the USA to work full time with Ruby!","code":"18S06","id":130,"kind":"session","position":46,"title":"Personal Dilemma: How to work with Ruby in Brazil?","title_en":"Personal Dilemma: How to work with Ruby in Brazil?","speakers":[{"abstract":"I currently work for Gonow Tecnologia, at S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil. We are a software house doing custom projects for clients. We have more than 20 people doing Ruby/Rails, iOS and Android development. I've been evangelizing Ruby and Rails in Brazil since around 2006. I released the first original Ruby on Rails written in Brazilian Portuguese in 2007. I organized the first Rails Summit Latin America in 2008, and have been repeating the conference in Brazil ever since. In 2010 we renamed the conference to RubyConf Brazil. I am trying to always evangelize software development best practices, but above all, trying to explain how to be better professionals overall. I also helped implement the first Ruby on Rails support in a shared hosting web environment at Locaweb, the largest hosting service in Latin America. I also worked as Brazil Rails Practice Manager at Surgeworks Inc, building and supporting a small offshore outsourcing group in Brazil to serve US clients. Prior to the Ruby community, I've been involved in the corporate SAP/Java market for a few years. And even before I've been in the first internet bubble. Overall, I've been developing software and delivering projects since the early 90's. You can find me at Twitter (@akitaonrails) or read my blog (http://www.akitaonrails.com), though most of my content is in Brazilian Portuguese.","abstract_en":"I currently work for Gonow Tecnologia, at S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil. We are a software house doing custom projects for clients. We have more than 20 people doing Ruby/Rails, iOS and Android development. I've been evangelizing Ruby and Rails in Brazil since around 2006. I released the first original Ruby on Rails written in Brazilian Portuguese in 2007. I organized the first Rails Summit Latin America in 2008, and have been repeating the conference in Brazil ever since. In 2010 we renamed the conference to RubyConf Brazil. I am trying to always evangelize software development best practices, but above all, trying to explain how to be better professionals overall. I also helped implement the first Ruby on Rails support in a shared hosting web environment at Locaweb, the largest hosting service in Latin America. I also worked as Brazil Rails Practice Manager at Surgeworks Inc, building and supporting a small offshore outsourcing group in Brazil to serve US clients. Prior to the Ruby community, I've been involved in the corporate SAP/Java market for a few years. And even before I've been in the first internet bubble. Overall, I've been developing software and delivering projects since the early 90's. You can find me at Twitter (@akitaonrails) or read my blog (http://www.akitaonrails.com), though most of my content is in Brazilian Portuguese.","code":"18S06:1","id":52,"name":"\u79cb\u7530\u30d5\u30a1\u30d3\u30aa\u8aa0","name_en":"Fabio Akita","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:56Z","id":48,"name":"Gonow Tecnologia","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:56Z"}]}],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:57Z","end_at":"2011-07-18T05:40:00Z","id":65,"place_area_id":1,"start_at":"2011-07-18T05:30:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:57Z","sessions":[{"abstract":null,"abstract_en":null,"code":"2011-07-18:S:break:2","id":132,"kind":"break","position":46,"title":"\u4f11\u61a9","title_en":"Break","speakers":[],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:57Z","end_at":"2011-07-18T06:40:00Z","id":67,"place_area_id":1,"start_at":"2011-07-18T05:40:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:57Z","sessions":[{"abstract":"\uff12\uff10\uff11\uff10\u5e74\uff11\uff10\u6708\u306b\u516c\u958b\u3055\u308c\u305f\u5206\u6563\u30aa\u30d6\u30b8\u30a7\u30af\u30c8\u74b0\u5883\u306eDeepConnect\u306e\u65b0\u3057\u3044\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u30d5\u30a7\u30fc\u30b9\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066\u7d39\u4ecb\u3057\u307e\u3059\u3002","abstract_en":"TBD.","code":"18S07","id":135,"kind":"session","position":46,"title":"\u5206\u6563\u30aa\u30d6\u30b8\u30a7\u30af\u30c8\u74b0\u5883DeepConnect\u306e\u65b0\u30d0\u30fc\u30b8\u30e7\u30f3\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066","title_en":"About New Version of DeepConnect for Distributed Object Environment","speakers":[{"abstract":"Ruby\u306e\u540d\u4ed8\u3051\u89aa\u3002\nIrb\u306e\u4f5c\u8005\u3002","abstract_en":"Ruby's Godfather.\nAuthor of Irb","code":"18S07:1","id":54,"name":"\u77f3\u585a\u572d\u6a39","name_en":"Keiju Ishitsuka","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:57Z","id":50,"name":"\u30da\u30f3\u30bf\u30a2\u30c9\u30d0\u30f3\u30b9\u30c8\u30e9\u30dc\u30e9\u30c8\u30ea\u30fc\u30ba","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:57Z"}]}],"sessions":[]},{"abstract":"\n\u30aa\u30d6\u30b8\u30a7\u30af\u30c8\u3068RDBMS\u3068\u3092\u30de\u30c3\u30d4\u30f3\u30b0\u3059\u308b\u30e9\u30a4\u30d6\u30e9\u30ea\u3084\u30c4\u30fc\u30eb\u3092\u3001\u300cO/R Mapper\u300d\u3068\u3044\u3044\u307e\u3059\u3002\n\nO/R Mapper\u3092\u4f7f\u3046\u3068RDBMS\u3092\u6271\u3046\u306e\u304c\u7c21\u5358\u306b\u306a\u308b\u3068\u671f\u5f85\u3055\u308c\u307e\u3059\u304c\u3001\u5b9f\u969b\u306b\u306fO/R Mapper\u306e\u4ed5\u7d44\u307f\u3092\u52c9\u5f37\u3057\u306a\u3044\u3068\u3001O/R Mapper\u306b\u632f\u308a\u56de\u3055\u308c\u308b\u3060\u3051\u306b\u306a\u308a\u307e\u3059\u3002\n\n\u672c\u767a\u8868\u3067\u306f\u3001O/R Mapper\u306e\u57fa\u672c\u7684\u306a\u4ed5\u7d44\u307f\u3068\u671b\u307e\u3057\u3044\u30a2\u30fc\u30ad\u30c6\u30af\u30c1\u30e3\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066\u8aac\u660e\u3057\u307e\u3059\u3002\n\u672c\u767a\u8868\u3092\u805e\u3051\u3070\u3001ActiveRecord\u3092\u542b\u3081\u65e2\u5b58\u306e\u307b\u3068\u3093\u3069\u306eO/R Mapper\u304c\u3001\u5fc5\u305a\u3057\u3082\u7406\u60f3\u7684\u3068\u306f\u3044\u3048\u306a\u3044\u3053\u3068\u304c\u308f\u304b\u308b\u3067\u3057\u3087\u3046\u3002","abstract_en":"`O/R Mapper' (ORM) is tool or library to map between Object and RDBMS.\nUsing ORM, you can handle RDBMS easier, but it is necessary for developers to understand underlaying technologies and techniques of ORM in order to use it effectively.\nIn this session, I'll explain about basic mechanism and recommended architechture of ORM.\nIf you join this session, you'll know that existing ORMs including ActiveRecord are anything but ideal.","code":"18S08","id":136,"kind":"session","position":46,"title":"O/R Mapper\u3092\u652f\u3048\u308b\u6280\u8853","title_en":"Underlaying Technologies and Techniques behind O/R Mapper","speakers":[{"abstract":"\u30d7\u30ed\u30b0\u30e9\u30de\u30fc\u3002","abstract_en":"Programmer.","code":"18S08:1","id":55,"name":"\u6851\u7530\u8aa0","name_en":"Makoto Kuwata","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:57Z","id":51,"name":"kuwata-lab.com","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:57Z"}]}],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:57Z","end_at":"2011-07-18T07:10:00Z","id":69,"place_area_id":1,"start_at":"2011-07-18T06:40:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:57Z","sessions":[{"abstract":null,"abstract_en":null,"code":"2011-07-18:S:break:3","id":138,"kind":"break","position":46,"title":"\u4f11\u61a9","title_en":"Break","speakers":[],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:58Z","end_at":"2011-07-18T08:20:00Z","id":72,"place_area_id":1,"start_at":"2011-07-18T08:10:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:58Z","sessions":[{"abstract":null,"abstract_en":null,"code":"2011-07-18:S:break:4","id":152,"kind":"break","position":57,"title":"\u4f11\u61a9","title_en":"Break","speakers":[],"sessions":[]}]}]},{"code":null,"floor":null,"id":2,"position":2,"title":"\u5927\u30db\u30fc\u30eb","title_en":null,"time_slots":[{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:43Z","end_at":"2011-07-16T01:30:00Z","id":2,"place_area_id":2,"start_at":"2011-07-16T01:00:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:43Z","sessions":[{"abstract":null,"abstract_en":null,"code":"2011-07-16:M:open:1","id":2,"kind":"open","position":1,"title":"\u958b\u5834","title_en":"Open","speakers":[],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:43Z","end_at":"2011-07-16T03:00:00Z","id":3,"place_area_id":2,"start_at":"2011-07-16T01:30:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:43Z","sessions":[{"abstract":null,"abstract_en":null,"code":"16MOP","id":3,"kind":"session","position":1,"title":"Opening","title_en":"Opening","speakers":[],"sessions":[]},{"abstract":"For the final RubyKaigi, we will discuss how Ruby changes can people's\nlives for the better and sometimes for worse.  The life stories\ninvolved will be used as a catalyst for looking at new features and\nproblems in Ruby and Rails, as well as ideas for where Ruby should go\nfor continued success.","abstract_en":"For the final RubyKaigi, we will discuss how Ruby changes can people's\nlives for the better and sometimes for worse.  The life stories\ninvolved will be used as a catalyst for looking at new features and\nproblems in Ruby and Rails, as well as ideas for where Ruby should go\nfor continued success.","code":"16M01","id":4,"kind":"session","position":1,"title":"Ruby Ruined My Life.","title_en":"Ruby Ruined My Life.","speakers":[{"abstract":"When he isn\u2019t ruining people\u2019s lives by writing software like phuby,\nenterprise, and neversaydie, Aaron can be found writing slightly more\nuseful software like nokogiri. To keep up his Gameboy Lifestyle, Aaron\nspends his weekdays writing high quality software for ATTi. Be sure to\ncatch him on Karaoke night, where you can watch him sing his favorite\nsmooth rock hits of the 70\u2019s and early 80\u2019s.","abstract_en":"When he isn\u2019t ruining people\u2019s lives by writing software like phuby,\nenterprise, and neversaydie, Aaron can be found writing slightly more\nuseful software like nokogiri. To keep up his Gameboy Lifestyle, Aaron\nspends his weekdays writing high quality software for ATTi. Be sure to\ncatch him on Karaoke night, where you can watch him sing his favorite\nsmooth rock hits of the 70\u2019s and early 80\u2019s.","code":"16M01:1","id":1,"name":"Aaron Patterson (tenderlove)","name_en":"Aaron Patterson (tenderlove)","organizations":[{"code":null,"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:43Z","id":1,"name":"AT&T Interactive","name_en":null,"updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:43Z"}]}],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:44Z","end_at":"2011-07-16T04:30:00Z","id":6,"place_area_id":2,"start_at":"2011-07-16T03:00:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:44Z","sessions":[{"abstract":null,"abstract_en":null,"code":"2011-07-16:M:lunch:1","id":7,"kind":"lunch","position":1,"title":"Lunch","title_en":"Lunch","speakers":[],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:44Z","end_at":"2011-07-16T05:30:00Z","id":7,"place_area_id":2,"start_at":"2011-07-16T04:30:00Z","updated_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:44Z","sessions":[{"abstract":null,"abstract_en":null,"code":"2011-07-16:M:announcement:1","id":8,"kind":"announcement","position":1,"title":"\u8af8\u9023\u7d61","title_en":"Announcement","speakers":[],"sessions":[]},{"abstract":"\u307e\u3082\u306a\u304fRuby 1.9.3\u304c\u30ea\u30ea\u30fc\u30b9\u3055\u308c\u307e\u3059\u3002\u7d30\u304b\u306a\u4ed5\u69d8\u30d0\u30b0\u306e\u4fee\u6b63\u3084\u6a5f\u80fd\u62e1\u5f35\u306f\u3042\u308b\u3082\u306e\u306e\u3001\u4e3b\u306b\u8a55\u4fa1\u5668\u3068\u30b9\u30ec\u30c3\u30c9\u3001\u304a\u3088\u3073\u30c6\u30b9\u30c8\u306e\u6539\u5584\u304c\u76ee\u7acb\u3064\u30ea\u30ea\u30fc\u30b9\u3068\u306a\u308a\u307e\u3057\u305f\u3002\u30ea\u30ea\u30fc\u30b9\u306b\u5411\u3051\u305f\u73fe\u5728\u306e\u72b6\u6cc1\u3092\u3054\u7d39\u4ecb\u3057\u3001\u307e\u305f\u5404\u90e8\u5206\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066\u306f\u8a73\u3057\u3044\u30b3\u30df\u30c3\u30bf\u304b\u3089\u304a\u8a71\u3057\u3057\u3088\u3046\u3068\u601d\u3044\u307e\u3059\u3002\u6b8b\u308a\u6642\u9593\u3092\u30b3\u30df\u30c3\u30bf\u3078\u306e\u8cea\u554f\u30b3\u30fc\u30ca\u30fc\u306b\u3057\u3088\u3046\u3068\u601d\u3044\u307e\u3059\u306e\u3067\u3001Ruby \u958b\u767a\u8005\u3078\u306e\u8cea\u554f\u304c\u3042\u308b\u65b9\u306f\u3053\u306e\u6a5f\u4f1a\u306b\u805e\u3044\u3066\u307f\u3066\u4e0b\u3055\u3044\u3002","abstract_en":"We will release Ruby 1.9.3 soon.  The main topics of 1.9.3 are evaluator, threads and the improvement of the test.  We will introduce the release progress of Ruby 1.9.3.  We will also show the each topics from corresponding committers.  The rest time will be Q&A session to Ruby committers. If you have questions to Ruby developers, please ask us.","code":"16M02","id":9,"kind":"session","position":1,"title":"Next version of Ruby 1.8 and 1.9","title_en":"Next version of Ruby 1.8 and 1.9","speakers":[{"abstract":null,"abstract_en":null,"code":"16M02:1","id":3,"name":"CRuby development team","name_en":"CRuby development team","organizations":[]}],"sessions":[]}]},{"created_at":"2013-04-23T11:52:44Z","end_at":"2011-07-16T05:40:00Z","id":9,"place_a